column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events
OTHER FREIGHT MOVED FORWARD DURING TRANSIT AND PUNCTURED PLASTIC DRUM.  K & D ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSED FOR PROPER CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER IN UNLOAD DOOR 4.  WEARING FULL P.P.E. I FOUND A 5 PART HAZMAT WITH A STAIN IN CORNER.  CONSULTED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID.  PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SPILL TUB AND REMOVED TO HAZMAT REWRAP AREA. INSPECTION SHOWED 1 OF 1 PLASTIC JUG LEAKED DUE TO LOOSE CAP. PRODUCT WAS REPACK IN SALVAGE DRUM AND R.T.S  WASTE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH D.M.P. PROGRAM.
ONE PAIL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A SEAM.  THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: WHILE LOADING, ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A PIECE OF STEEL.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ONE TOTE TANK WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  THE CAP WAS MISSING THE GASKET.  THE SHIPPER PROVIDED A GASKET AND IT WAS INSTALLED BY CERTIFIED RESPONSE PERSONEL.  THE TOTE WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.
TWO DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED WITH LEAKS AROUND THE BUNG.  THE LEAKAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE BUNGS TIGHTENED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

TRAILER WAS FOUND LEAKING.  A CERTIFIED RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE THE TOTE WAS FOUND DAMAGED AND LEAKING FROM IMPROPER BLOCKAGE AND BRACING.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A DOT APPROVED DRUMS WITH CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: GATX 75270, NOVEMBER 4, 2000, SOUTH JERSEY DIVISION TANK CAR GATX 75270, LOAD LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS (PROPANE), LOADED AT TOSCO, TRAINER REFINERY, ON 11/4/00. AT COMPLETION OF LOADING, LOADING RACK PERSONNEL PERFORMED ROUTINE LEAK CHECK OF ALL VALVES INSIDE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA WITH COMBUSTIBLE GAS INDICATOR (CGI). NO INDICATIONS OF LEAKS NOTED. THERMOMETER WELL WAS OVERFILLED WITH GLYCOL SOLUTION, SPILLING OUT OVER THE MANWAY PRESSURE PLATE AREA. THE SPILLED GLYCOL AROUND THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE INDICATED AN INTERMITTENT BUBBLE ORIGINATING FROM UNDERNEATH THE "B" SIDE OF THAT VALVE'S MOUNTING FLANGE. THE AREA WAS WIPED CLEANED OF GLYCOL AND USE OF CGI WAS REPEATED WITH NO READING REPORTED. THE CAR WAS FORWARDED WITH ADDITIONAL CARS ON THE SCHEDULED SWITCH, WHICH WAS ALREADY IN THE  PROCESS OF TAKING PLACE. TOSCO REPORTS THE ON-DUTY YARDMASTER WAS MADE AWARE OF THE FINDINGS, AND ALSO ADVISED THAT DANA RAILCARE, EDGEMOOR, DE, WERE ENROUTE TO INSPECT AND EFFECT ANY NECESSARY REPAIRS PRIOR TO THE CAR BEING FORWARDED TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION. AFTER APPLYING LARGE QUANTITIES OF LEAK DETECTION SOLUTION TO ALL VALVES INSIDE THE HOUSING, DANA NOTED A SMALL INTERMITTENT BUBBLE FROM THE AREA ORIGINALLY REPORTED THE SECUREMENT NUTS ON THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE WERE MADE TIGHTER THAN REQUIRED. THE ENSUING LEAK TEST ALSO INDICATED A SIMILAR BUBBLE FROM THE "B" SIDE OF THE VAPOR VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE. UPON RECOMMENDATION FROM DANA, TOSCO REQUESTED A SPECIAL SWITCH FROM CONRAIL, TO MOVE THE CAR BACK TO THE REFINERY RACK, WHERE THE CAR IS BEING UNLOADED, DEPRESSURIZED AND VALVES AND ASSOCIATED O-RINGS INSPECTED AND/OR REPLACED. THE SWITCH INTO THE REFINERY WAS CONDUCTED AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS, 11/4/00. AT NO TIME WERE ANY READINGS INDICATED ON THE CGI BY EITHER TOSCO OR DANA.
DRIVER THOUGHT TANK WAS EMPTY SO HE DISCONNECTED THE HOSES AND PRODUCT CAME RUNNING OUT.

WHEN THE CITY DRIVER BACKED TO THE DOCK, (RICO THOMAS) OPENED THE DOOR TO GET HIS HANDTRUCKS OFF HE NOTICED A SMELL IN HIS TRAILER. HE INFORMED ME.  I OBTAINED THE BILL FROM HIM AND CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK ON THE HAZMAT IN QUESTION.  THE DRIVER EXPLAINED TO ME THAT WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY ON A STEEP DRIVEWAY AT A CUSTOMERS HOME A SKIP SLID BACK A BUMPED A BOX OF HAZMAT AT THAT TIME THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF A LEAK.  ONLY WHEN HE GOT BACK AT THE TERMINAL DID HE NOTICE THE SMELL.  I LOOKED AT THE BOX IN QUESTION.  THERE WASN'T ANY DAMP PLACES ON THE BOX BUT THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM IT.  I PUT ALL THE PROTECTIVE HAZMAT GEAR THAT WE  HAVE AT THE TERMINAL ON, (RUBBER GLOVES, APRON, FACE SHIELD.)  I OPENED THE BOX AND SAW ONE CONTAINER.  IT TOOK ONE AWHILE TO FIND IT BUT ONE OF THE CONTAINER HAD A VERY SLIGHT LEAK IN THE SEAM ON THE BOTTOM.  WE HELD THIS ONE GAL CONTAINER IN OUR HAZMAT BAY AND SENT THE REMAINING PIECES TO FINAL DEST.  AT THE MOST 3 OUNCES MAY HAVE LEAKED OUT AND HAD ALREADY EVAPORATED BEFORE THIS EXCEPTION WAS WRITTEN UP.  COPY OF THE BILL IS ATTACHED.

UPON DESCENT CREW NOTICED STRANGE ODOR. UPON LANDING, A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE PALLET ON THE A/C DID NOT REVEAL SOURCE OF ODOR. PALLET WAS REMOVED FROM A/C TO FURTHER INVESTIGATE ONCE PALLET WAS BROKEN DOWN, IT WAS SEEN THAT ONE OF THE STEEL DRUMS HAD LEAKED SOME OF ITS CONTENTS. IT WAS REPORTED TO HAVE LEAKED DUE TO OVER PRESSURIZING (INTERNAL) IT WAS NOT DETERMINED IF THE DRUM WAS OVERFILLED OR IF THE DRUM'S SEAL (LID) FAILED.

RAMP NOTICED ODOR AROUND TANK. EMI CALLED AND ERG ARRIVED AND FOUND THAT VALVE WAS LOOSE VERY MINIMUM FLUID LOSS. ERG SOAKED UP FLUID AROUND VALVE AND RETIGHTENED VALVE. ERG HANDLED DISPOSAL OF ANY MATERIALS/FLUID.

column168: OUR SPOTTER REPORTED THAT 584648 WAS LEAKING WHITE PAINT IN OUR YARD.  I CHECKED THE BILLS AND SAW THAT THE ONLY LIQUID WAS FLAMMABLE INK ON PRO 1107941898 LOADED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. I HAD THE TRAILER PUT TO THE DOCK.  USING HAZMAT GEAR (GLOVES, BOOTS, BREATHING APPARATUS) AND 10-25LBS BAGS OF CAT LITTER,  I UNLOADED THE TRAILER.  THERE WERE 4 DRUMS.  ONE WAS HALF EMPTY. WITH HELP I FLIPPED IT OVER INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THERE WAS NO CARDBOARD UNDERNEATH THE DRUMS AND THE BOARDS OF THE PALLET WERE 3 INCHES A PART.  IT APPEARED A FORKLIFT BLADE OR SOMETHING HAD GONE BETWEEN THE BOARDS.  THERE WAS A 4 INCH LAND INDENTATION THAT ENDED WHERE THE THE BOTTOM CURLS INTO A LIP.  THAT IS WHERE THE HOLE WAS. IT WAS MINUTE.  IT SLOW LEAKED.  IT COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED HAD THE SHIPPER USED DUNNAGE BETWEEN THE DRUMS & THE PALLET.

FREIGHT PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT DURING LOADING CAUSING SPILL.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN IN CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOR THE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS ROBERT HARPER AND DONALD OSBORNE DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THIS PACKAGE FROM THE AREA, OPENED IT AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE FOLLOWING POSSIBLE REGULATED ITEM.  3X32 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES, STONE CARE INTERNATIONAL, INTERNATIONAL STONE POLISH, COUNTERTOP POLISH MARBLE & GRANITE, MARKED "KEEP AWAY FROM OPEN FLAME AND OTHER IGNITION SOURCES". THE LID ALSO DID NOT HAVE A PROTECTIVE LINER UNDER THE CAP.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED IT, AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THEY PLACED THE RECOVERY DRUM IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE LEAKED WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WERE NO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0333.

column168: GATX 48006, LOAD OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS FOUND LEAKING WHILE IN TRAIN Q548-20 AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN WINCHESTER, KY. column168: THIS CAR WAS FOUND LEAKING DURING TRAIN MOVEMENT IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S STANLEY YARD AT WALBRIDGE, OH.  INSPECTION FOUND LIQUID SPLASHED OUT FROM AROUND THE FILL HOLE COVER OF THE CAR.  THE BOLTS WERE SECURED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

AFTER RECEIVING CAR IN INTERCHANGE FROM THE ABERDEEN AND ROCKFISH RR, PERSONNEL IN THE YARD AT FAYETTEVILLE DETECTED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM TANK CAR PLMX 33893. THE CAR WAS PLACED IN AN ISOLATED AREA AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED. THE CONSIGNEE (CAR LESSEE) WAS NOTIFIED AND APPRISED OF THE SITUATION. AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO INSPECT AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE ROD WAS LOOSE. AFTER TIGHTENING THE PACKING NUT APPROXIMATELY 1/8 OF A TURN THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE LEAK HAD BEEN A VERY MINOR ONE, AND COULD ONLY BE DETECTED UPON CLOSE INSPECTION. ALL OTHER VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND SECURE. AFTER THE REPAIR WAS MADE TO THE GAUGING DEVICE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AND WAS RE-ROUTED TO A REPAIR SHOP FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPLACEMENT OF THE GAUGING DEVICE PACKING GLAND.

GATX 21204 DERAILED BEING PULLED FROM THE SHIPPERS FACILITY. THE TANK CAR ROLLED DOWN AN EMBANKMENT AND CAME TO REST IN AN INVERTED 5 O'CLOCK POSITION. THE TANK CAR LEAKED FROM AROUND THE CONTROL ROD OF THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV). THE RELEASE RATE WAS 12 GALLONS A HOUR AND THE TOTAL AMOUNT RELEASED WAS 110 GALLONS. THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE AREA OF THE IMMEDIATE DERAILMENT. THE CAR WAS TRANSLOADED DUE TO THE DAMAGE TO MECHANICAL FEAURES AND SAFETY APPLIANCES.

column168: ACFX 76595 WAS OBSERVED BY A CSXT YARD CREW YARD DURING FLAT SWITCHING MOVEMENT TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE MANWAY. THE COVER HAD BEEN TIGHTENED WITHOUT USING THE CRISSCROSS OR STAR PATTERN FOR BOLT TIGHTENING AND THAT ATTRIBUTED TO THE MANWAY BEING COCKED AND NOT FORMING AN ADEQUATE SEAL ON THE NOZZLE.

A PALLET OF FIVE GALLON CONTAINERS WAS BEING MOVED IN THE WASTE STORAGE AREA OF TEN DAY TRANSFER FACILITY. THE DRUMS WERE TRIPLED STACKED ON THE PALLET AND ONE OF THE STACKS FELL. A BUNG ON ONE OF THE DRUMS CRACKED AND SPILLED ONE QUART OF AQUEOUS BRAKE SOLUTION INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH  ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED. THE CRACKED BUNG WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FOUR POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM HANDLING AND SECUREMENT PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

AS THE DRIVER WAS ARRIVING AT THE FACILITY, HE STOPPED AT THE GATE AND A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM TIPPED OVER IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK. THE CITRIC ACID SOLUTION IN THE DRUM SPILLED INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT, BUT NONE OF THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED BEYOND THE FACILITY'S LOT. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 625 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET IN LINDEN, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER  DRUM CLOSURE AND BLOCKING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO  MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS TRUCK AT A 10 DAY TRANSFER FACILITY. WHILE UNLOADING, A 16 GALLON STEEL DRUM FELL OVER AND THE LID CAME OFF SPILLING THREE GALLONS OF PETROLEUM NAPHTHA SOLVENT INTO THE FACILITY'S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE WASTE GENERATED CONTAINERIZED. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON DRUM HANDLING AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.
DELIVERED 1 PALLET CLEAR SWS INTACT 26 PCS- OF 5 GAL BUCKET OF ADHESIVE, 1 BUCKET WITH BACK SIDE PIERCED- THE SHRINK WRAP WAS PULLED WHERE DAMAGED OCCURRED.

WHILE IN TRANSIT, A 55 GALLON DRUM OF PRODUCT WAS DAMAGED. APPARENTLY, THE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A PALLET JACK. APPROXIMATELY, TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE SEATTLE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE INCIDENT AND PLACED ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT. IMMUNEX CORPORATION PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP. column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS ENTERING I-65 FROM THE ENTRANCE RAMP.  ANOTHER TRUCK (UNKNOWN) MOVED FROM THE RIGHT LANE TO THE LEFT LANE AND RAN SOMEONE OFF THE ROAD.  THAT VEHICLE LOST CONTROL AND RAN INTO THE PATH OF OUR VEHICLE, FORCING THE DRIVER TO THE SHOULDER AND PARTIALLY OFF THE ROADWAY, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO ROLL.  WE LOST 127 GALLONS OUT OF THE DOME OVER THE 8 HOUR PERIOD, OR APPROX. 16 GALLONS PER HOUR. THE INTERSTATE WAS CLOSED DUE TO THE POSITIONING OF TOW TRUCKS HOLDING THE UNIT, KEEPING IT FROM ROLLING FURTHER DOWNHILL, NOT AS A DIRECT RESULTS OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.
DUPLICATE DELIVERY. DELIVERY WAS MADE THE DAY BEFORE.

column168: UNIT BEING OPERATED IN A RESIDENTIAL AREA BY DRIVER WITHOUT AUTHORIZATION WHILE TRANSPORTING A REGULATED MATERIAL.  DRIVER REPORTEDLY ATTEMPTED TO CROSS RAILROAD GRADE.  ON FIRST ATTEMPT LANDING GEAR OF THE TRAILER BECAME LODGED ON THE RAIL.  DRIVER BACKED UNIT UP, ATTEMPTED TO CROSS AGAIN, CUTTING THE TURN TOO SHORT, CAUSING TRAILER TO TRACK INTO DITCH AND OVERTURN.  TRACTOR WAS ACROSS TRACKS PARTIALLY OVERTURNED.  PRODUCT BEGAN LEAKING FROM VENT PIPE ADJACENT TO DOME LID.  APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED TO ENVIRONMENT.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNIT OF COMPANY WAS ABLE TO BUILD TEMPORARY CONTAINMENT BERM WITH CLEAN SOIL.  APPROXIMATELY 400 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS VACUUMED FROM RAIL DITCH.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED (APPROX. 12 YARDS) AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.  RECOVERY AND CLEAN UP OPERATIONS SUPERVISED BY REPRESENTATIVES OF LA DEQ AND LA HAZMAT OF STATE POLICE. RAILROAD CROSSING AND RAIL CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY SEVEN (7) HOURS. KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN (KCS) RAILROAD NOTIFIED AND HAS PERSONNEL ON SCENE.  TRAINS WERE STOPPED FOR THE DURATION OF THE CLOSURE PERIOD. DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO AREA MEDICAL FACILITY, TREATED, AND RELEASED.  RESULTS OF DRUG/ALCOHOL TESTS PENDING AT THIS TIME.

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 25 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED, PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM, AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED 5-GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE 1/2 WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1 CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED PAIL WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 10-GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A SKID CONTAINING 90 PAILS OF PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED AT THE 3/4 MARK OF THE TRAILER. THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE ABSORBENT WASTE AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, 15 GALLON DRUM WHICH REMAINS AT THE ADELANTO, CALIFORNIA ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSAL COORDINATION. THE DAMAGED PAIL OF PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO ANOTHER 15 GALLON DRUM WHICH WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, THREE WET CARTONS EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE-GALLON METAL PAILS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING ELEVEN WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTONS, FREE PRODUCT AND DAMAGED PAIL WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE ELEVEN UNAFFECTED PAILS WERE REPACKAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, 50 POUND PAPER BAG WAS DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A SHOVEL, AND A BROOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 35 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED BAG WAS RETAPED, AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED. ONE EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE EYES. THE EMPLOYEE'S EYES WERE THEN FLUSHED OUT WITH WATER AND NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS SOUGHT. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED 5-GALLON STEEL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 40-GALLON PLASTIC-LINED FIBER DRUM. THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A 8-GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM. BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column168: TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED LEAKING PRODUCT IN A TRAILER AT THE TERMINAL YARD. APPARENTLY, A  55 GALLON DRUM OF PRODUCT WAS CRUSHED BY HEAVY TOP FREIGHT. APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT RELEASED. THE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS LOCATED IN THE FIRST 1/4 OF THE TRAILER AND HAD APPLICABLE LABELING. TERMINAL PERSONNEL USED ABSORBENT WIPES TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB THE FREE PRODUCT. THE ABSORBENT WIPES AND OTHER CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 35 GALLON FIBER DRUM. THE 35 GALLON FIBER DRUM IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED 55 GALLON DRUM OF PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON STEEL OVER PACK DRUM. THE 85 GALLON STEEL OVER PACK DRUM CONTAINING THE DAMAGED 55 GALLON DRUM OF PRODUCT IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE ON THE DOCK AT THE TERMINAL, ONE DAMAGED 1 GALLON CAN IN A CARTON OF 4 CANS WAS DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE CAN WAS PUNCTURED BY A NAIL ON THE SKID. THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS AND THE DAMAGED CAN WERE PLACED INTO A 5 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT. THREE UNAFFECTED CANS WERE RE-BOXED AND WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY 55 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE. THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE INITIAL CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO TWO 85 GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS, TWO 25 GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS AND ONE 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE FIVE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION AT THE TERMINAL. HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS COORDINATED THE REMAINDER OF THE  CLEANUP. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM. THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED. EIGHT EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT. THEY WERE TAKEN TO OCCUPTATIONAL METHODIST HOSPITAL IN INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA AS A PRECAUTION AND WERE RELEASED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED, 15 GALLON STEEL DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUMS WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT. FOUR SEASONS ENVIRONMENTAL OF NASHVILLE, TENNESSEE RESPONDED AND PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION, A BROOM, AND A DUSTPAN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, DAMAGED DRUMS AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO TWO, 35 GALLON FIBER OVERPACK DRUMS. THE OVERPACK DRUMS WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT RAGS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, AND DAMAGED PAIL WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE ON THE DOCK, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED ONE LEAKING, 275 GALLON POLY TOTE. APPROXIMATELY SIX OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP SUITS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE REMAINDER OF THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FOURTEEN-GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED THE SEAL WAS REPLACED AND THE TOTE WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, EIGHT LEAKING 55-GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE 1/2 WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE LEAK WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT WHICH CAUSED THE BUNGS ON THE DRUMS TO LOOSEN.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PPE, ABSORBENTS TOWELS AND WATER.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 10-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR  DISPOSITION.  THE LOOSE BUNGS WERE TIGHTENED ON THE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE, 55-GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE.  FOUR SEASONS ENVIRONMENTAL OF NASHVILLE, TENNESSEE RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED FIFTY POUND BAGS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE TEASPOON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONFINED TO THE TOPS OF THE BAGS. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED GLOVES TO WRAP THE SKID, THE TWO DAMAGED BAGS, FREE PRODUCT, AND THE TWO UNAFFECTED BAGS IN PLASTIC. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, 1-GALLON CONTAINERS WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL FOUR CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS, AFFECTED CARTON, AND THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 25-GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM THAT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, FOUR WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR, 1-GALLON CONTAINERS, WERE DISCOVERED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO HEAVY TOPFREIGHT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS, DAMAGED CONTAINERS, AND AFFECTED CARDBOARD WERE PLACED INTO TWO, 15-GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS TO BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE UNAFFECTED CONTAINERS WILL BE RECOUPED AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

FREIGHT WAS OFFLOADED FROM HTX TRUCK ELP 150 AND STAGED IN THE HAZMAT AREA FOR CUSTOMER PICKUP. WHEN CUSTOMER ARRIVED TO PICK UP FREIGHT, LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED AND REPORTED. THE SPILL CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AT 1030 AND I SPOKE WITH AN ASSOCIATE. I ALSO NOTIFIED THE EMERGENCY CONTACT ON THE HAZMAT DEC AT 1035 AND SPOKE WITH DON AT INFOTRAC. I NOTIFIED BOB JOHNSON/HDY AT APPROX 1100. PICTURES HAVE BEEN TAKEN. THIS SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 3 STEEL 5 GALLON CANS. THEY WERE NOT PALLETIZED. FREIGHT WAS LOOSE LOADED AT REAR OF TRAILER AND HAD TOPPLED OVER. THIS WAS PREVENTABLE. PHOTOS ATTACHED.
THE DRIVER WAS PUMPING INTO STORAGE TANK AND IT OVERFILLED AND RAN DOWN TANK AND BUILDING. THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP IN THE STORAGE TANK AREA.

column168: IN TRANSIT FROM OUR TERMINAL IN ATLANTA ONE BOX SHIFTED AND ENDED UP LEAKING.  A TOP ON ONE OF THE CONTAINERS WAS NOT FASTENED TIGHT ENOUGH SOME OF THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT.

FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS UNLOADING OTHER FREIGHT OFF TRAILER BEFORE SEEING THE DRUM.  PUNCTURED DRUM AS HE UNLOADED THIS FREIGHT.  THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE USED TO PROTECT DRUM WHICH MAY HAVE PREVENTED THIS FROM HAPPENING CONTACTED SHIPPER FOR INSTRUCTIONS, SHIPPER WANTS SOUTHEASTERN TO DISPOSE OF PRODUCT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE LOADING, METER MALFUNCTIONED CAUSING DRIVER TO HAVE TO DRAIN 2-3 BUCKETS OF PRODUCT FROM TRAILER.  SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OCCURRED WHILE DRAINING WAS IN PROCESS.  CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED BY HESS EMPLOYEES WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENTS REPORTED.
EMPLOYEE HAD COMPLETED DELIVERY AND WAS ROLLING HOSE WHEN APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF RESIDUAL FUEL WAS RELEASED ON TO LOT. CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED USING SPEED DRY WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENTS REPORTED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AFTER OUR DRIVER RECEIVED THE OKAY TO UNLOAD  HE OPENED THE VALVE ON THE TRAILER AND STARTED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK TO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK WITH THE PUMP ON THE TRACTOR.  AS HE WAS ADJUSTING THE BY-PASS ON THE PUMP,  PRESSURE BUILT UP IN THE DISCHARGE LINE WHICH CAUSED THE HOSE END TO BLOW OFF AND SPRAY PRODUCT ON OUR DRIVER AND EQUIPMENT.  DRIVER HAD HIS PPE ON BUT WHEN HE REMOVED HIS FULL GOGGLES SOME PRODUCT DRIPPED ON AND IN HIS EYES.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT REVEALED THAT THE VALVE ON THE CONSIGNEE'S DISCHARGE LINE WAS CLOSED.  ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND OIL DRY WAS APPLIED TO PRODUCT AND WAS CLEANED BY CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL.

DRIVER WAS OFF LOADING WITH AIR PRESSURE.  AT THE END OF THE UNLOADING THE SURGE OF AIR CAUSED THE STORAGE TANK TO BUBBLE OVER.  THE DRIVER AND THE MEAD PAPER EMPLOYEE RINSED DOWN THE STORAGE TANK INSIDE THE CONTAINMENT WALL AND WASHED DOWN INTO THE PLANT SEWER WHICH GOES INTO THE PLANT WATER TREATMENT SYSTEM.

WHILE UNLOADING, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A DAMAGED TOTE BAG OF PRODUCT.  APPARENTLY, THE TOTE BAG WEIGHING 1,100 POUNDS WAS PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  APPROXIMATELY, FIVE POUNDS OF PRODUCT RELEASED.  HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

column168: WHILE ENROUTE TO THE CONSIGNEE THE DRIVER ROLLED OVER AND DOWN A RAVINE.  STATE & LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE ON SCENE AND A CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP. THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO ST. ALPHONSES HOSPITAL IN BOISE,  ID AND TREATED FOR A SHOULDER AND LEG INJURY.  HE WAS RELEASED.  THE TRAILER WAS RIGHTED AND THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A DIFFERENT TRAILER.  NO FURTHER INCIDENT NO INJURIES.

FILE:3032 D, DATE: 11/22/2000, SHIPPER ACROS ORGANICS, AWB & EDS 7916728940 DSD. ON 11/22/2000 AT 0338 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 208 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. PART TIME HAZ. MAT TECHNICIANS CHRISTOPHOR CHAPPS AND DONALD OSBORNE, AS WELL AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR FRANCE K. VANCE, DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BLUE STEEL DRUM THAT HAD APPEARED TO BE LEAKING AROUND THE BUNG CLOSURE.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, THIS WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE AROUND THIS CLOSURE.  THIS DRUM CONTAINED 25 L OF ETHYL ACETATE, WHICH WAS DENTED AS WELL. THEY PLACED THE DRUM INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY  PLACED THE  BAGGED SHIPMENT   INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THEY FORWARDED THIS DRUM ONTO IT'S DESTINATION.  THE AREA INVOLVED RECEIVED NO PRODUCT FROM THIS LEAKING SHIPMENT.  THERE WAS EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES IN THIS EMPLOYEE.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THIS WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ATTACHED TO THIS DRUM. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. CLEAR OF SCENE 0369.

column168: A TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH WASTE HEADING FOR A DISPOSAL FACILITY AND DURING THE PRE-TRIP INSPECTION, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT IT WAS LEAKING ON THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA. IT WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED ALONG WITH THE 30 GALLON DRUM IN A 55 GALLON OVERPACK. THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE WASTE PICK-UP WAS COUNSELED ON DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS CUT-OFF BY A PASSENGER VEHICLE CAUSING THE TRUCK TO JACKKNIFE, RESULTING IN THE ROLL-OVER OF THE PUP.  THIS CAUSED THE FAILURE OF THE TANK AND RESULTED IN AN EXPLOSIVE FIRE OF THE PRODUCT.  PUBLIC SAFETY RESPONDERS SUPPRESSED THE FIRE AND ABSORBED/CONTAINED THE MATERIALS.  THE KELLERSTRASS RESPONSE COMPANY ASSISTED AND PLACED CONTAINMENT AND ABSORBENT BOOMS IN THE CANAL. THEY ALSO REMOVED THE RESIDUAL DEBRIS FROM THE FREEWAY, THE RIGHT-OF-WAY AND DISPOSED OF ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL AND DEBRIS.  UDOT REPAIRED THE ASPHALT. column168: DRIVER SPOTTED LOADED CARGO TANK AT CHARLESTON, WV TERMINAL.  DURING THE POST-TRIP INSPECTION, THE DRIVER NOTICED A PRODUCT SMELL.  THE DRIVER INSPECTED THE INTERNAL/EXTERNAL VALVE AND NOTICED A SMALL LEAK (DRIP).  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE AND CONTAINED THE RELEASED PRODUCT.  THE LOAD WAS THEN TRANSLOADED ONTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK SO THAT THE DAMAGED TRAILER COULD  BE REPAIRED.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT (APPROX. 8 OZ) THAT WAS CAPTURED IN THE BUCKET WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE ON-SITE TANK WASH.

column168: SHIPMENT CAME IN DOUBLE STACKED ON TOP OF ANOTHER SKID OF FREIGHT AND HAD FALLEN BACKWARDS AT AN ANGLE.  FROM THE FORKLIFT DRIVERS PERSPECTIVE THE PAILS OF LIQUID COULD NOT BE SEEN.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PICK THE PALLET UP AND STRAIGHTEN IT BEFORE TAKING IT OFF THE OTHER PALLET.  THE PAIL HAD FALLEN THROUGH THE SLATS IN THE PALLET SO WHEN THE DRIVER WENT UNDER THE PALLET.THE FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURED THE PAIL.  PREVENTIVE MEASURES DO NOT DOUBLE STACK LIQUIDS AND MAKE SURE THEY ARE CLEARLY VISIBLE IN THE SHIPMENT.  ALSO USE A GOOD PALLET WITH CARDBOARD UNDER THE FREIGHT.  ALSO FORKLIFT DRIVER SHOULD RIGHT THE FREIGHT BEFORE ATTEMPTING TO PICK IT UP.

UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL SIXTEEN CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY SIXTEEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO HEAVY TOP FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FOUR DAMAGED CARTONS, AND THE SIXTEEN DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED IN A 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT THE 3/4 MARK IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND EVAPORATED DURING TRANSIT.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES.  THE GLOVES AND THE LEAKING DRUM WERE PLACED INTO AN EIGHT GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM THAT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING, 55 GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 20 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS LEAKING DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO ONE, 15 GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM, AND ONE, 50 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DRUM IS THE ONLY PIECE IN THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: ON ARRIVAL AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP AFTER COMPLETING SEVERAL OTHERS, THE I/C DRIVER ENCOUNTERED A STRONG ODOR OF PAINT IN THE TRAILER. ON INVESTIGATION HE FOUND TRIPLE STACKED PALLETS OF PLASTIC SHEETING.  SOME RED INK HAD SPLASHED ONTO SOME OF THE ROLLS.  WHEN THE SHEETS WERE MOVED HE COULD SEE A PALLET CONTAINING DRUMS AND TWO PAILS STACKED ONE ON THE OTHER.  THE PAILS HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY THE PALLETS OF THE SECOND AND THIRD TIERS OF SHEETING.  ONE PAIL WAS NEARLY EMPTY AND THE OTHER WAS NEARLY FULL.  BOTH WERE CONTINUING TO LEAK.  THE DRUMS APPEARED TO BE UNDAMAGED.  DRIVER ACQUIRED A NUMBER OF PLASTIC BAGS AND TWO CARDBOARD BOXES FROM REGAL.  HE PUT THE DAMAGED PAILS INSIDE THE BAGS, AND INTO THE BOXES.  HE CONTINUED TO A LOCAL CARTAGE CARRIERS'S FACILITY.  HE LEFT THE UNDELIVERABLE SHIPMENTS THERE TO BE OVERPACKED FOR LATER PICK UP AND RETURN TO THEIR SHIPPER.

ON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR PRESENT IN THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER FOUND TWO PAILS ON ONE PALLET WITH CUTS IN DENTS ABOUT 1/2 WAY UP THE SIDES.  IT APPEARS AS IF THE PALLET WAS RAMMED DURING LOADING.  CONSIGNEE REFUSED DELIVERY OF THE DAMAGED PAILS BUT TOOK THEM FOR DISPOSAL AS THEY HAVE THE CAPABILITY TO DO SO PROPERLY.

WHILE THE CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVER WAS PICKING UP THE DRUM FROM THE TRAILER WITH A DRUM CLAMP, THE EDGE OF THE CLAMP PUNCTURED THE DRUM IN MID-SECTION.  APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS WAS LOST.  THEY USED SAW DUST AND FLOOR SWEEP TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE DAMAGED DRUM WITH A CLEAR DELIVERY RECEIPT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DRIVER CALLED FROM AN INTERMEDIATE STOP TO REPORT THAT WHEN HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR, HE ENCOUNTERED A STRONG ODOR IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWED BY LIQUID LEAKING ONTO THE GROUND.  HE WAS ABLE TO OBSERVE TWO DRUMS NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER THAT ARE LYING ON THEIR SIDES.  HE CANNOT GET TO THEM TO LIFT THEM UP.  CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO USE ITEMS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO BLOCK ANY STORM DRAINS THAT MIGHT BE EXPOSED AND TO PUT A SOCK ACROSS THE TRAILER DOOR.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED BY SITE PERSONNEL AND IS ON LOCATION.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL CLIMBED OVER THE OTHER FREIGHT AND UP RIGHTED THE FALLEN DRUMS.  THEY NOTED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS FROM THE BUNGS.  THEY ESTIMATED THAT THERE WAS ABOUT 20 GALLONS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, PLUS WHATEVER WENT ON THE GROUND.  THE CARRIER RETAINED A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE REMEDIATION.  A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SEWER DEPARTMENT WAS THERE WITH THE SEWER MAPS TO ATTEMPT TO DETERMINE WHERE ANY OF THE LIQUID MAY HAVE GONE.  THEY DETERMINED THAT THE STORM DRAIN INVOLVED DOES NOT GO ANYWHERE.  IT IS FULL OF MUD.  THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT ENTERED IT IS DESCRIBED AS MINIMAL.  THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED, CONFERRED WITH THE SEWER DEPARTMENT PERSON AND PERFORMED NECESSARY SITE REMEDIATION.  THEY UNLOADED THE TRAILER, CLEANED UP THE FREE LIQUIDS FROM THE FLOOR AND RELOADED IT.  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO THE CARRIER'S NEAREST FACILITY.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE SPILLAGE WAS ABSORBED AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  THE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.

DURING UNLOADING AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE PAIL WAS FOUND TO HAVE FALLEN OFF OF THE PALLET THAT IT WAS ON. IT WAS LEAKING FROM A CRACK IN A DENT ON ITS SIDE.  THE PAIL WAS OVERPACKED AND HELD OFF TO AWAIT THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

column168: DRUMS WERE STRAPPED TO THE TRAILER WALL AT THE TRAILER'S TAIL. DURING UNLOADING AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP, A FORK LIFT STRUCK AND PIERCED ONE OF THE DRUMS.  THE DRIVER GOT THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE BUT NOT BEFORE LOSING SOME PRODUCT ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  SOME OF IT RAN UNDER OTHER FREIGHT FARTHER UP IN THE TRAILER.  HAZMAT RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO PERFORM A CLEAN UP.  ON ARRIVAL THE CONTRACTOR UNLOADED THE TRAILER, OVERPACKED THE DRUM THAT WAS DAMAGED AND CLEANED THE SPILL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE DRIVER CONTINUED AND DROPPED THE DRUM AT A FACILITY OF THE CARRIER.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 08/24/OO AT APPROXIMATELY 1125 HOURS, WHILE INSPECTING THE UNION PACIFIC RR INTERCHANGE IN THE CN/IC MAYS YARD, HARAHAN, LA., FRA INSPECTOR (HAZMAT) NOTED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO TANK CAR GATX 81095.  A CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM BETWEEN THE TANK CAR AND THE VALVE.  ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO SECURE THE LEAK TO NO AVAIL.  THE LEAK WAS NOT CONSTANT; SMALL SHORT BURSTS EVERY THREE TO FOUR MINUTES.  A COLLECTION DEVICE WAS PLACED UNDER THE TANK CAR VALVE AND IT WAS MOVED BACK TO THE SHIPPER UNDER 49CFR174.50, SAFE MOVE.  FRA INSPECTOR WAS CONSULTED BY THE SHIPPER.

AN EMPLOYEE OF REGGIO'S NOTICED TANK CAR WAS LEAKING AND CALLED THE FIRE DEPT.  THE FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED, AND CALLED THE RAILROAD.  THE RAILROAD RESPONDED ASSISTING THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT (DISTRICT 6) TEAM.  THE TANK CAR WAS TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR WHICH WAS COMPLETED AT 20:20 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, NOV. 29, 2000. THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE FLANGE ABOVE THE VALVE.  THIS TANK CAR HAD A TEN YEAR INSPECTION IN MAY, 2000 AT MILTON, PA.

column168: ON 11/17/00, MOTOR CARRIER WAS FILLING A PROPANE STORAGE TANK AT THE PLANKINTON PUBLIC SCHOOL AND DUE TO A POOR CONNECTION, THERE WAS AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF PROPANE INTO THE AIR AND ONTO THE SNOW AND GROUND. THE PROPANE STORAGE TANK BEING FILLED WAS APPROXIMATELY TWO FEET FROM THE FOUNDATION OF THE SCHOOL BUILDING. CARRIERS EMPLOYEES REPAIRED THE CONNECTION, TURNED THE GAS SUPPLY FROM THE PROBLEM TANK OFF, AND WENT INTO THE SCHOOL TO NOTIFY SCHOOL AUTHORITIES THAT THERE HAD BEEN A SMALL SPILL OF LP GAS AND THAT THERE WOULD PROBABLY B A SMALL ODOR. THE SCHOOLS CUSTODIAN REPLIED THAT HE WOULD WATCH THE SITUATION AND WOULD RETURN THROUGHOUT THE EVENING TO MONITOR THE ODOR. LATER THAT EVENING THE MITCHELL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS SUMMONED ALONG WITH THEIR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM TO HELP FIND THE SOURCE OF THE LP ODOR AND WHAT ACTION TO TAKE. THERE WAS AN EXPLOSION FOLLOWING THAT RESULTED IN TWO FATALITIES, ONE INJURY, AND TOTAL LOSS OF THE SCHOOL. THERE WERE MECHANICAL REPAIRS MADE AROUND THE BOILER AREA OF THE SCHOOL AS WELL AS LP REGULATORS BEING REPLACED THE DAY PRIOR TO AND THE DAY OF THE EXPLOSION. THE INVESTIGATION CONTINUES AS TO THE SOURCE OF THE LP ODOR.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE RELEASE OCCURRED ON THE NORTH SIDE OF HIGHWAY 197 APPROXIMATELY 8 MILES WEST OF ELKHORN CITY, KENTUCKY ON NOVEMBER 18,2000. THE TANKER WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND AND SWERVED TO MISS AN ON-COMING CAR IN A CURVE. IT THEN TRAVELED ACROSS THE WESTBOUND LANE AND CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE IN THE DRAINAGE DITCH ON THE NORTH SIDE ON HIGHWAY 197. THE TANKER WAS CARRYING APPROXIMATELY 7804 GALLONS OF KEROSENE. SOON AFTER THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED, FUEL BEGAN TO LEAK FROM A BREACH IN THE TANKER. JONES OIL COMPANY, INC. ASSISTED WITH PUMPING OFF THE REMAINING FUEL FROM THE TANKER. THE SIDE OF THE TANKER WAS PUNCTURED, THUS, LEAKING FUEL IMPACTED SOIL UNDER THE WRECKAGE. ENVIRO PRO AND WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL WERE UTILIZED FOR SITE CLEAN UP. SITE CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES BEGAN ON THE DAY OF THE SPILL. APPROXIMATELY 40 TONS OF SOIL WERE EXCAVATED FROM THE DITCH LINE AND TAKEN TO A WASTE MANAGEMENT LANDFILL IN LILY, KENTUCKY. SOIL EXCAVATION DIRECTLY BELOW THE SPILL LOCATION WAS LIMITED DUE TO THE PRESENCE OF A WATER MAIN. LIQUID WASTE RECOVERED FROM AN AFFECTED STREAM USING A VAC TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO PETRO MAX IN CARNEGIE, PA FOR DISPOSAL. ON THE AFTERNOON OF NOVEMBER 19TH, CLEANUP ACTIVITIES AND PLANS FOR THE FUTURE WERE DISCUSSED WITH REGULATORY OFFICIALS FROM KENTUCKY AND THE USEPA. THE AMOUNT OF FUEL PRESENT UNDER THE ROAD IS UNCERTAIN. HOWEVER, AFTER EVALUATING THE QUANTITIES OF FUEL RECOVERED USING THE VAC TRUCK, THE AMOUNT OBSERVED TO BE RECOVERED BY ABSORBENTS, AND THE RESULTS OF FLUSHING THE SPILL AREA, THE QUANTITY OF FUEL STILL TO BE RECOVERED IS PREDICTED TO BE SMALL.

column168: UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOOR AT THE CONSIGNEE, THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED STRONG PUNGENT FUMES. HE IMMEDIATELY MOVED AWAY FROM THE TRAILER AND CALLED THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN. THE DRIVER INDICATED THAT THERE WAS NOTHING LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER AND FROM WHAT HE SAW THERE WAS NO LIQUIDS ON THE FLOOR, EITHER. THE CARRIER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER FOR ADVICE AND MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS. ON THE ADVICE OF THE SHIPPER, THE CARRIER RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A SPILL CONTRACTOR. THE DRIVER COMPLAINED THAT INITIALLY HE HAD FELT LIGHT HEADED, BUT WAS NOW FEELING WELL. HE COULD AND DID MOVE THE TRAILER TO A DOWNWIND POSITION, AND DENIED ENTRY TO THE AREA TO ALL EXCEPT THE CONTRACTOR. THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON LOCATION AND REVIEWED THE MSDS. USING APPROPRIATE PPE, THEY MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AND LEARNED THAT SEVERAL TANKS HAD INADEQUATE SEALS ON THEIR MANWAY COVERS. THEY WERE ABLE TO STABILIZE AND SECURE THE TANKS ENOUGH TO ALLOW THEM TO BE UNLOADED FROM THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER REPORTED TO THE CARRIER THAT HE WAS FEELING NO ILL EFFECTS FROM HIS INITIAL CONTACT WITH THE ODOR IN THE TRAILER. THE CARRIER'S TECHNICIAN ALLOWED THE DRIVER TO TAKE HIS VEHICLE TO THE CARRIER'S NEARBY FACILITY. ON ARRIVAL THERE, THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO A MEDICAL FACILITY FOR EXAMINATION. HE WAS RELEASED TO FULL DUTY WITHOUT FURTHER TREATMENT. HE HAS NOT COMPLAINED OF ILL EFFECT NOR SOUGHT ADDITIONAL TREATMENT SINCE.

column168: THE DRIVER HAD PICKED UP FROM THE SHIPPER, THEN CONTINUED TO HIS NEXT ASSIGNED PICK UP POINT.  WHEN HE OPENED THE TRAILER THERE,HE OBSERVED AND REPORTED TO THE CARRIER WHITE SMOKE AND AN ACRID SMELL IN THE TRAILER.AS HE WAS CLOSE TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF  FIRE, THE CARRIER DIRECTED HIM RETURN TO THE FACILITY. THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE SHIPPER FOR TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE. THE SHIPPER'S CHEMIST STATED THAT HYDROBROMIC ACID WAS REACTING WITH ALUMINUM FLOORING CREATING ALUMINUM BROMIDE. THE WHITE SMOKE WAS THE WATER VAPOR BEING PRODUCED FROM THE CHEMICAL REACTION. THE CHEMIST INDICATED THAT THERE WAS NO INHALATION HAZARD FOR THIS. HE PROVIDED THE MSDS. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE VEHICLE AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, THE HAZMAT TECHNICIAN CHECKED AND FOUND THAT THERE WAS NO SMOKE PRESENT. THE TECHNICIAN SUPERVISED THE UNLOADING OF THE TRAILER TO GET TO THE SUSPECTED LEAKING FREIGHT. UPON REMOVING THE PALLET OF DRUMS CONTAINING THE HYDROBROMIC ACID, PRODUCT STARTED LEAKING AGAIN, AND THE SAME REACTION OCCURRED. INSPECTION OF THE DRUMS ON THE PALLET REVEALED THAT ONE DRUM WAS SITTING ON A NAIL THAT WAS PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLET. THE CARRIER THEN RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO COMPLETE A CLEAN UP AND OVERPACK THE DAMAGED DRUM. THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT THEN CONTINUED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DURING UNLOADING, THE CONSIGNEE'S FORK LIFT STABBED ONE DRUM.  THEY TOOK THE DRUM AND IMMEDIATELY PUT ITS CONTENTS INTO THEIR PROCESS. THEY ALSO HANDLED ALL ASPECTS OF CLEANING THE SPILLAGE.

DURING STRIPPING OF THE PICK UP TRAILER AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND BY THE FORK LIFT OPERATOR TO HAVE A HOLE IN ITS SHELL ABOUT 2" DOWN FROM THE TOP.  IT HAD LEAKED A SMALL QUANTITY OF MATERIAL.  THE TRAILER WAS PRE-LOADED BY THE SHIPPER.  THE DRIVER WHO PICKED THE TRAILER UP OBSERVED ALL SUBSEQUENT LOADING THAT TOOK PLACE AND STATES THAT NO OTHER EVENT OCCURRED THAT WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM.

column168: WHEN OFFERED FOR DELIVERY, THE TANK WAS REFUSED DUE TO WETNESS AT THE TOP, COMING THROUGH THE MANWAY COVER GASKET.  IT WAS TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S NEARBY FACILITY AND HELD WHILE THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR REPAIRS.  ONCE DONE, THE TANK WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

ON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE, DRUMS HAD LIQUID ON THE HEADS. CONSIGNEE BELIEVES THAT IT IS PRODUCT, AND IS COMING FROM DEFECTIVE BUNG GASKETS.  THEY CLEANED UP AND ACCEPTED ALL.  THEY ALSO WIPED UP ANY FREE LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THEY PROVIDED THE DRIVER WITH THE MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT.

column42: AMINE, FLAMMABLE, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, FLAMMABLE, CORROSIVE N.O.S.
column168: ON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE, THERE WAS AN OVERPOWERING ODOR IN THE CARRIER'S TRAILER.  THE CONSIGNEE COULD NOT MAKE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AS A RESULT.  THEY DETERMINED TO REFUSE THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT AND RETURN IT.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE CARRIER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN ADVISED THE DRIVER NOT TO DEPART THE PREMISES UNTIL THE SOURCE OF THE PROBLEM WAS IDENTIFIED AND CORRECTED.  THE TECHNICIAN RETAINED A CONTRACTOR, THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER FOR THE M.S.D.S.  AFTER ARRIVING AND MAKING INITIAL ENTRY, THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THEY HAD ACCESSED AND INSPECTED ALL CYLINDERS.  VALVES ON ALL EIGHTEEN WERE LOOSE FROM 1/4 TO 1/2 TURN.  THEY TIGHTENED ALL.  IN ADDITION, 3/8" PLUGS WERE MISSING FROM FIVE CYLINDERS.  IN THE PROCESS OF CORRECTING THE DEFICIENCIES THEY FOUND ONE CYLINDER WITH A CROSS-THREADED PLUG.  IT WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE LEAKAGE.  THE CONTRACTOR CONSULTED WITH THE SHIPPER TO DETERMINE HOW TO PROPERLY PROCEED.  THEY ADVISED THAT THE PRODUCT HAS A BOILING TEMPERATURE OF +35o F.  THE PLUG CANNOT BE REMOVED UNTIL THE PRODUCT TEMPERATURE IS REDUCED TO THAT LEVEL.  THE OTHER CYLINDERS HAD THEIR DEFICIENCIES CORRECTED AND WERE DELIVERED.

WHILE A FORK LIFT OPERATOR WAS PLACING THE TANK ONTO IT STAGING AREA, THE VALVE FELL OFF ALLOWING A LOSS OFF APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF RESIDUAL MATERIAL.  THE VALVE WAS RESECURED AND THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE ABSORBENT WAS THEN PLACED INTO TWO RECOVERY DRUMS AND HELD FOR DISPOSAL.  AFTER INSPECTION THE TANK CONTINUED TO ITS DESTINATION.

A DERAILMENT OCCURRED ON NOVEMBER 21, 2000, AT APPROXIMATELY 0600 HOURS. THE TRAIN WAS TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 7-10 MPH CARRYING 33 CARS TOTAL (23 LOADED, 10 EMPTY).  CARS 23, 26, 32, AND 33 DERAILED WITH CARS 32 AND 33 LANDING ON THEIR SIDES.  CAR 33 WAS CARRYING TOLUENE.  NO LEAK WAS OBSERVED AT FIRST; HOWEVER, AT 0830 HOURS A LEAK WAS NOTICED AND STOPPED BY HULCHER EMERGENCY SERVICES AT 0930 HOURS.  THE ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY, THE FEDERAL EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  ALL IMPACTED SOIL WAS TO BE IMMEDIATELY EXCAVATED BY HULCHER'S HAZMAT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  ALL TANK CARS WERE RIGHTED AT 1400 HOURS TO ASSESS DAMAGE TO THE TRACK.  CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT IS UNDER INVESTIGATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: (A/B) OUR TRUCK DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN A ROLL OVER ACCIDENT AT HWY 41 SOUTHBOUND ON RAMP IN APPLETON, WI.  THE DRIVER WAS GOING TO FAST FOR THE CURVE AND THE LOAD SHIFTED DUE TO THE SPEED OF THE TRUCK GOING THRU THE CURVE.  THIS ON RAMP IS A VERY SHARP CURVED ROAD. THE DRIVER GOT OUT WITH MINIMAL INJURIES.  THE TRUCK AND THE FREIGHT WAS A TOTAL LOSS. WE CONTRACTED SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES, INC.  OUT OF FOUND DU LAC,  WI  TO DO THE CLEAN UP AND EXCAVATION.  SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES USED A VACUUM  TRUCK TO REMOVE THE LIQUID FROM A THE  DITCHLINE.  A TOTAL OF 150 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED FROM THE DITCHLINE AND PLACED INTO  THREE 55- GALLON DRUMS, AND TRANSPORTED TO SUPERIOR'S TSD FACILITY IN PORT WASHINGTON, WI FOR DISPOSAL PROCESSING.  SUPERIOR PROCEEDED TO SCHEDULE AND COORDINATE EXCAVATION AND REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL. A TOTAL OF 105.70 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP WAS SHIPPED TO SUPERIOR'S TSD FACILITY IN PORT WASHINGTON, WI FOR DISPOSAL PROCESSING.  A TOTAL OF (4) CLOSURE SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED AT VARIOUS LOCATIONS TO CONFIRM PROPER CLEANUP.  LABORATORY ANALYSIS INDICATED THAT TRICHLOROETHYLENE WAS PRESENT IN THE CLOSURE SAMPLES AND BACKGROUND SAMPLES. TRICHLOROETHYLENE WAS NOT PRESENT IN THE CONFIRMATION SAMPLE. THIS INDICATES THAT THE TRICHLOROETHYLENE WAS PRESENT PRIOR TO THE PRINTERS INK SPILL.  THE EXCAVATION WAS BACKFILLED, SEEDED, AND MULCHED TO RESTORE SITE CONDITIONS. IN CONCLUSION, WE HAVE HAD A BAD SITUATION HAPPEN TO OUR COMPANY BUT WE HAVE USED THIS ACCIDENT IN OUR SAFETY MEETINGS TO TEACH OTHER DRIVERS HOW IMPORTANT THEIR JOB IS ON THE ROAD!

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: APPARENTLY BETWEEN THE LAST LOAD HAULED AND THIS ONE (WHICH SPAN APPROX. 30 DAYS) A PIN HOLE HAD DEVELOPED IN THE LINING, LETTING THE PRODUCT AT SOME POINT MAKE CONTACT WITH THE METAL UNDER THE LINING.  EVEN THOUGH THE TRAILER WAS EMPTY THE CORROSION STILL TOOK PLACE EATING A SMALL DIME SIZE HOLE IN THE BELLY OF THE TANK AT THE REAR.  THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THE SMALL HOLE AND PROCEEDED TO KERR-MCGEE'S FACILITY IN SAVANNAH, GA TO BE LOADED.  THE OPERATOR AT KERR MCGEE GOT EVERYTHING READY TO START LOADING, WHILE THE DRIVER WAS STANDING BESIDE THE TRAILER THE OPERATOR TURNED THE PUMP ON TO LOAD.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TOLD HIM TO SHUT IT BACK OFF. (ONLY A COUPLE OF SECONDS ELAPSED) THEY WENT TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND NOTICED A STEADY SMALL STREAM COMING FROM THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED ME FOR INSTRUCTIONS.  I IMMEDIATELY ASKED + RECEIVED THE NAME AND A PHONE NUMBER OF A SUPERVISOR FOR THAT PARTICULAR LOADING STATION.  THE DRIVER INFORMED ME THAT THE TANK HAD STOPPED LEAKING AND WAS EMPTY.  I ASKED IF THEIR WAS ANYWAY PRODUCT COULD STILL BE IN THE FORWARD SECTION OF THE TANK.  HE REPLIED NO BECAUSE THE TANK WAS ON A GRADUAL PITCH TO THE REAR AND THAT ALL PRODUCT FORWARD OF THE HOLE WOULD RUN OUT OF THE HOLE AND THAT THE HOLE WAS ONLY ABOUT 4 INCHES FROM THE REAR, AND THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE REAR HEAD IN TAMPERED FORCING THE PRODUCT ALSO BACK TO THE HOLE.  I ASKED IF WE HAD ANY SOIL CONTAMINATION TO OCCUR. HE REPLIED NO.  ALL SPILLAGE IS CONTAINED IN THE CONCRETE LOADING PAD.  I ASKED HIM FOR AN ESTIMATED AMOUNT SPILT.  HE REPLIED 50 TO 55 GALLONS.  I IMMEDIATELY MADE CONTACT WITH THE SUPERVISOR IN CHARGE, AND ASKED HOW I COULD BE OF ASSISTANCE.  I OFFERED TO COME DOWN MYSELF TO ACCESS THE SITUATION, SEND A CLEAN-UP CREW, OR ANYTHING HE SUGGESTED.  HE REPLIED THAT NONE OF THAT IS NECESSARY.  THE LEAK IS COMPLETELY STOPPED, THE PRODUCT IS SAFETY CONTAINED, AND THAT IT WOULD ONLY TAKE A FEW BAGS OF SOMETHING TO NEUTRALIZE AND ABSORB WHAT HAD SPILLED.  I OFFERED TO PAY FOR ANY AND ALL CHARGES HE DEEMED NECESSARY FOR THE CLEAN-UP AND  DISPOSAL OF THE MATERIAL AND THE COST OF THE PRODUCT LOST.  HE REPLIED BY SAYING THAT THEIR WAS SUCH A SMALL AMOUNT LOST AND THAT CLEAN-UP TIME AND SUPPLIES WOULD BE SO MINIMAL THAT I NEED NOT TO WORRY ABOUT ANYTHING, HE HAD IT COVERED AND TAKEN CARE OF.  HE PROCEEDED TO THANK ME FOR THE QUICK ACTIONS OF MY DRIVER FOR ALERTING THE OPERATOR SO QUICKLY, THAT A POTENTIAL LARGER SITUATION WAS ABLE TO BE AVOIDED.  HE DID ASK ME IF I WOULD LEAVE THE TANKER THERE UNTIL THE HOLE COULD BE PATCHED BEFORE LEAVING THERE PROPERTY.  I AGREED.  THE TANK WAS PATCHED AND APPROVED FOR DEPARTURE FROM THEIR FACILITY.  SINCE THAT INCIDENT, FAULTLESS TANK LINES, INC. HAS NEITHER TRANSPORTED 77% SULFURIC NOR USED ANOTHER HERESITE LINED TRAILER FOR PRODUCT TRANSPORT. FAULTLESS TANK LINES DONE AN EXTREME AMOUNT OF RESEARCH AND THAT RESEARCH INDICATED THAT HERESITE P403 LINING WAS THE MOST SUITABLE LINING FOR

column168: FILE: 3030 D, DATE: 11/08/2000, SHIPPER: OKLAHOMA FIXTURE COMPANY, AWB# TUL 5791999942 QNS. ON 11/08/2000 @ 0059 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT GATE B101 ON AIRCRAFT N909AX OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN MATTHEW GROSVENOR AND ELWOOD BOHI, AS WELL AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES, DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF A LEAKAGE. THEY REMOVED THIS PIECE FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND BEGAN THEIR INSPECTION. UPON THIS INSPECTION THEY FOUND 2 X 1 GALLON METAL RECEPTACLES, EACH WRAPPED IN "SHRINK WRAP. THESE WERE SURROUNDED BY PACKING PEANUTS. THESE DID NOT HAVE POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THEIR LIDS, WHICH DID NOT COME LOOSE. BOTH OF THESE LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES EACH FROM THESE LOOSE CLOSURES. THE LABELS ON THESE METAL CANS HAS BEEN OBSCURED BY THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX, AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS FORWARDED ONTO IT'S DESTINATION. THE AREA INVOLVED WAS CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER, AND WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED. THERE WERE 3 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THIS ODOR. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WITH THESE EMPLOYEES. NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED. THIS WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. THERE ARE PICTURES OF THIS SHIPMENT ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE. CLEAR OF SCENE 0130.

THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR THE PRODUCT, ONE GALLON OF URETHANE, LISTS A FLASH POINT OF 79 DEGREES FARENHEIT. AS THE OUTER PACKAGING WAS NOT SENT WITH DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELING, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION, THE PACKAGE IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.  FAA AGENT ANDREW JOHNSON WAS NOTIFIED AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD FOR HIS INVESTIGATION.

column168: A PASSENGER ARRIVED IN BOS OFF AN AIR NOVA FLIGHT FROM YHZ ON HIS WAY TO SAP.  HE HAD PACKED SEVERAL BOTTLES OF FUEL INJECTOR CLEANER ALONG WITH OTHER ITEMS IN A CARDBOARD BOX AND CHECKED IT AS BAGGAGE FOR A FLIGHT TO JFK.  THE TOP OF EACH BOTTLE WAS SEALED WITH SILVER DUCT TAPE, HOWEVER ONE BOTTLE LEAKED.  THE BOX WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE AA BAGROOM BEFORE IT WAS LOADED ONTO THE FLIGHT. ONCE THE PASSENGER WAS LOCATED THE BOX WAS OPENED AND ITEMS SUCH AS TRANSMISSION FLUID, PAINT AND ENGINE FLUSH WERE FOUND ALONG WITH THE FUEL INJECTOR CLEANER.  THE PASSENGER WAS ADVISED THAT HE COULD NOT TRAVEL WITH THESE ITEMS AND AA SEIZED THEM.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: AFTER REACHING CRUISE ALTITUDE THE FLIGHT ENGINEER (MICHAEL ENGLAND PROCEEDED WITH CARGO CHECK.  UPON RETURNING UP THE RIGHT SIDE OF MAIN DECK PALLET POSITION FR, HE NOTICED A STRONG ODOR EMITTING FROM THE PALLET.  THE SMELL WAS SIMILAR TO PAINT THINNER.  AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY THE LOADMASTER AND FLIGHT MECHANIC A 1 GALLON CAN OF PAINT OR GLUE OR WHATEVER WAS FOUND.  THE CAN WAS DENTED, WET AND SOMEWHAT CONCEALED IN A PLASTIC BAG FOUND IN A BOX ON THE PALLET. NO HAZMAT PAPERWORK WAS GIVEN TO THE CREW FROM ADVANCE CARGO AND THE CREW ASSUMED NO HAZMAT ON BOARD.  THE CAPTAIN (CAPTAIN SWABY) WENT TO INVESTIGATE AND DETECTED A VERY STRONG ODOR AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CREW STAIRS.  A DECISION WAS MADE TO RETURN TO MIAMI BECAUSE OF AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT SITUATION.  MIAMI OPERATIONS AND ATLAS JFK DISPATCH WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION AND THE DECISION TO RETURN TO MIAMI.  MIAMI CENTER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE POSSIBLE HAZMAT SITUATION AND NO EMERGENCY WAS DECLARED.  THE LOAD MASTER AND FLIGHT MECHANIC FELT DIZZY AND LIGHT HEADED AND WAS PUT ON CREW O2 AND GOGGLES FOR THE CREW BUT IT WAS DETERMINED THE CREW WAS FINE SO IT WAS NOT USED. (NO FUMES IN COCKPIT).  LANDING WAS UNEVENTFUL AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS MET THE ACFT AT THE GATE.  THE CREW DID A NORMAL DEPARTURE FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS DECIDED THE 1 CAN WAS NOT ENOUGH TO CAUSE SUCH A HEAVY FUME SMELL SO ALL CARGO WAS DOWNLOADED AND BROKEN DOWN FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  AFTER ARRIVING AT FLT OP CAPT SWABY CONTACTED MITCH HACKETT, DUTY MANAGER, AND DIRECTOR OF OPERATIONS, MIKE CITRANO, FOR PROPER ATLAS AIR MANAGEMENT NOTIFICATION.

HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SUPERVISOR KAREN SCHOTERMANN RECEIVED THE PAGE.  SHE THEN NOTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AREA MANAGER JAMES CURTIS WHO AUTHORIZED SENDING 2 PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS SANDY WILLIAMS AND WILLIAM HENDERSON. THEY LEFT ILN STATION AT 1010 AND ARRIVED AT THE NCV STATION AT 1130.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE ACENE THEY NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF WHITE POWDER ON THE FLOOR NEAR A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX.  THEY OPENED THIS PACKAGE AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY NOTICED THE GLASS RECEPTACLE ON THE INSIDE WAS SHATTERED. THE AIRCRAFT LANDED SAFELY INTO THE FEDEX RAMP FACILITY IN EL PASCO AND THE CREW EVACUATED THE AIRCRAFT WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE NEXT TWO FREIGHT POSITIONS WERE ALSO OFFLOADED AND FOUND NOT TO CONTAIN THE PACKAGE.  THE FREIGHT CONTAINER IN THE FOURTH LOADING POSITION WAS OFFLOADED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN THE CULPRIT SHIPMENT. column168: FRANK, PHOENIX YARDMASTER, UNION PACIFIC REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 202460 LEAKED MATERIAL FROM THE TOP OF THE DOME WHEN MOVED INSIDE THE PHOENIX YARD. FRANK STATED THE CAR DEPARTMENT INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND FOUND NO HOLES; THEREFORE, THEY ASSUMED THE LEAK CAME FROM SOMETHING LOOSE IN THE DOME. FRANK CONTINUED BY STATING THE MATERIAL WHICH LEAKED OUT OF THE TANKCAR EVAPORATED FROM OFF THE SIDE OF THE TANKCAR AND THERE WAS NO MATERIALS CURRENTLY ON THE TANKCAR. DENNIS JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED HE WOULD DISPATCH A CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE TANKCAR. MANAGER JOHNSON REPORTED THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE ALL LOOSE. HE ALSO ADVISED THAT THE SECURING CAPS TO THE LIQUID AND VAPOR LINES WERE BOTH LOOSE, AS WAS THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP. ALL EXCEPTIONS WERE CORRECTED AND THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. MANAGER JOHNSON CONFERRED WITH GARY DEVLIN AND DEBBIE MURRAY, AGP ETHANOL (SHIPPER) AT 402-496-7809. WAYBILL INFORMATION LISTED MARK DITSWORTH AS THE EMERGENCY CONTACT AT 402-460-4402 FOR TANKCAR UTLX 202460 BUT UPRR AND CHEMTREC WERE BOTH UNSUCCESSFUL IN MAKING CONTACT. AGP ETHANOL CONCLUDED BY STATING THEY WOULD HANDLE ALL PROBLEMS WITH BILLING AND EMERGENCY NOTIFICATION NUMBER AND INSPECTION PROCEDURES AT THEIR LOADING PLANT.

column168: ON 112200 AT APPROXIMATELY 1045 A.M. MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL OF A GAS ODOR AT STRANG YARD.  REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, CALLED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE AND ASKED THEM TO RESPOND SINCE THEIR OFFICE IS ONLY ABOUT 5 MINUTES AWAY.  EAGLE PERSONNEL COULD NOT SMELL A GAS ODOR.  HOWEVER, THEY DID FIND ONE CAR THAT HAD A CHEMICAL ODOR NEARBY.  REEDER CLIMBED ON TOP OF UTLX 201435 AND NOTICED AN ACRYLATE ODOR.  REEDER OBSERVED THE MANWAY GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE.  REEDER REMOVED A SEAL WITH THE NUMBER 060435 FROM THE MANYWAY COVER.  UPON OPENING, IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT THE GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED, THE COVER CLOSED, AND THE BOLTS TIGHTENED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: INVESTIGATION OF ABOVE LEAKING CAR REVEALED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET SECURING CAP ON THE CAR.  THE CAP WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE MISSING A GASKET.  A NEW GASKET WAS APPLIED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED UNTIL THE CAR BUILT UP PRESSURE.  AT THIS TIME A SMALL DRIP STARTED AROUND THE CAP.  THE CAP WAS RESECURED USING TAPE ON THE THREADS AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAK.  ON 11-20-2000 THE CAR WAS MOVED INTO THE PLANT FOR OFF LOADING.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF A POSSIBLE BAD BOTTOM BALL VALVE WHICH WAS CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO BUILD UP IN THE SECURING CAP AREA.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: ON ABOVE DATE AND TIME, MGR. CTS DENNIS JOHNSON WAS ADVISED OF TANK CAR GATX 98868 ON TRACK 18 WITHIN TUCSON YARD LEAKING FROM THE TOP. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TANK CAR MR. JOHNSON OBSERVED A STEADY STREAM OF PRODUCT COMING FROM THE VALVE AREA ON TOP OF THE CAR.  WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF THE TUCSON FIRE DEPT., MR. JOHNSON WAS ABLE TO BLEED OFF THE AIR FROM THE TANK AND STOP THE LEAK.  INVESTIGATION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THE BOLT PATTERN ON THE LIQUID LINE SECURING PLATE WERE LOOSE AND ONE STUD LOCATED "A" END, RIGHT SIDE WAS BROKEN OFF. THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND A BLIND FLANGE PLACED OVER THE LIQUID LINE.  A SHORT BOLT WAS USED ALONG WITH THE NORMAL BOLTS TO SECURE THE PLATE.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION AND CAR WAS PLACED IN FUTURE BAD ORDER STATUS TO BE HOME SHOPPED AFTER OFF LOADING.  VALVE COVER LID HAD INTACT SEAL HIGH PLANS CORP. 5499.

DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATION, THE TANK CAR WAS FOUND BY YARD PERSONNEL, TO HAVE A SIGNIFICANT VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  UNION PACIFIC SWITCHMAN J.W. BROUSSARD APPARENTLY INHALED SOME OF THE AMMONIA VAPORS AND COMPLAINED OF TIGHTNESS IN HIS CHEST. BROUSSARD WAS TAKEN TO POINTE COUPEE GENERAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  THE TANK CAR WAS IN THE BOWL YARD AND THIS RESULTED IN THE HUMP BEING SHUT DOWN.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC, TRIAD NITROGEN THE SHIPPER, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY AND PAT BAKER ENV. SERVICES.  PAT BAKER INC, UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF MR. HERBY BART RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  THIS INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE WAS LEAKING FROM THE MOUNTING FLANGE AS WELL AS THE VALVE THROAT, EVEN THOUGH THE VALVE APPEARED TO BE CLOSED.  THE MOUNTING FLANGE STUD NUTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THIS SECURED THE LEAKAGE.  THE VALVE PLUG WAS ALSO TIGHTENED.  TRIAD NITROGEN SEAL #10512 WAS REMOVED FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND REPLACED WITH SEAL #PTRAC 791414.  ONCE SECURED, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM DAN RIVA RECEIVED A TELEPHONE CALL THAT ONE OF OUR TRUCKS WAS ON FIRE ON HAWKINS POINT ROAD.  DAN TOLD ME AND I IMMEDIATELY HEADED TOWARD THE SCENE.  DURING MY DRIVE I CALLED GORDON AND HE ALSO HEADED TOWARD THE SCENE FROM BALTIMORE.  GORDON CALLED ME AROUND 1 PM AND SAID THAT HE WAS STUCK IN TRAFFIC ON THE BRIDGE, BUT HE COULD SEE THE TRUCK FROM THE BRIDGE AND IT WAS TOTALLY DESTROYED.  I THEN CALLED DAN AT THE OFFICE AND HAD HIM REPORT IT TO THE INSURANCE COMPANY.  GORDON, TONY PAPPAS, AND I ALL ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AROUND 1:30 PM AND BEGAN TO ASSES THE SITUATION.  THE TRUCK HAD HIT A TELEPHONE POLE AND FLIPPED OVER ON ITS TOP.  WHILE UPSIDE DOWN THE TRUCK HAD CAUGHT FIRE AND WAS TOTALLY DESTROYED.  THE FIRE HAD MELTED THE TANK RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 2600 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL DOWN THE STREET.  WHEN WE ARRIVED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY PUT OUT THE FIRE AND THE DRIVER HAD BEEN TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL.  WE DID NOT SEE ANY NEWSPAPER REPORTERS OR CAMERA CREWS ON THE SITE WHEN WE ARRIVED OR AT ANY TIME THAT I WAS THERE UNTIL 4:30 AM FRIDAY MORNING.  GORDON WALKED THE WHOLE SITE TAKING PICTURES AND THEY SHOULD BE DEVELOPED AND BACK EARLY NEXT WEEK.  DURING THIS TIME WE FIGURED THAT THE DRIVER (OSWALD GROSS) MIGHT HAVE BECOME CONFUSED DUE TO THE NEW TRAFFIC PATTERN, LOST CONTROL, HIT A TELEPHONE POLE AND FLIPPED THE TRUCK OVER ON ITS SIDE.  A SPECTATOR AT THE SCENE HAD MENTIONED THAT THE TELEPHONE POLE HAD BEEN HIT AND REPLACED SEVERAL TIMES.  HOW HE ESCAPED WITH OUT BEING KILLED IS A MIRACLE.  A&A ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND STARTED THE CLEAN UP AROUND 3:45 PM.  THEY HAD TEN MEN WITH TWO PALLETS OF SPEEDY DRY AND BEGAN TO CLEAN THE STREET AND INTERSECTIONS OF HAWKINS POINT ROAD AND CHEMICAL DRIVE.  DURING THIS TIME A VAC TRUCK, BACKHOE, FRONT-END LOADER, AND DUMP TRUCK ALSO ARRIVED TO CLEAN UP THE OIL IN THE GROUND AROUND THE SPILL AREA AND THE OIL THAT SPLASHED OVER THE CURB.  MOST OF THE WORK COULD NOT START UNTIL MISS UTILITY ARRIVED AND MARKED THE AREA.  THE MEN STARTED AT THE INTERSECTION FIRST AND SPEEDY DRI DOWN AND BEGAN TO CLEAN IT UP IMMEDIATELY.  THIS OPERATION AT THE INTERSECTION TOOK ABOUT 2 HOURS.

column168: ON 11/13/00 RMCC CONTACTED CTS MGR. M. KELLY AND ADVISED THAT A DERAILMENT HAD OCCURRED IN HARRISON, TX. AND THAT NINE KNOWN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CARS WERE INVOLVED.  KELLY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND OBSERVED THE ABOVE TANK CAR LEAKING FROM A PUNCTURE IN THE HEAD OF THE CAR ON THE "B" END.  IT APPEARED THAT THE PUNCTURE WAS CAUSED BY IMPACT WITH NATX 35871 DURING THE DERAILMENT.  THE CAR APPEARED TO BE LEAKING ABOUT 5 GALLONS PER MINUTE.  THE LEAK WS STOPPED BY THE USE OF A MAGNETIC PATCH APPLIED TO THE CAR.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED INTO TRANSPORT TRUCKS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. MANAGER COOPER LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN ROW E5, SPACE #377, AND NOTED A SMALL AREA OF DRIED PRODUCT ON THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER POST OF THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, DEVELOPED THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON DRUMS,DOUBLED STACKED. THE LADING WAS HELD IN PLACE WITH THE USE OF TY-PATCH APPEARED TO BE PROPERLY APPLIED FOR THE MOST PART,  HOWEVER,THE CORNER POST AND TAPE SUPPORT TO PREVENT THE MATERIALS FROM 'DROOPING' WAS MISSING. THE LAST ROW (DOORWAY) ON THE TOP AND BOTTOM TIERS WAS FINISHED OFF WITH 3 EACH DRUMS. THE DRUMS APPEARED TO BE THE NEWER STYLE WITH THE INVERTED ROLLING HOOPS. THE BILEVEL SEPARATION CONSISTED OF 3/8 INCH PLYWOOD, WHICH WAS CUT SEVERAL INCHES SHORT, ALLOWING THE TOP TIER DRUMS TO OVER HANG THE PLYWOOD ON BOTH SIDES NEAR THE SIDE WALLS. THE BOTTOM TIER DRUMS HAD MOVED ROUGHLY 2 INCHES TOWARDS THE DOORWAY AS EVIDENCED BY THE EXTENSION OF THE BOTTOM TIER DRUMS PAST THE TOP TIER DRUMS. THERE WAS A TDI SENSOR PATCH APPLIED TO THE TY-PATCH AT THE REAR DOORS, WHICH HAD TURNED PINK,INDICATING THE TDI HAD BEEN PRESENT. A SHOCK SENSOR HAD BEEN APPLIED TO THE LEFT SIDE WALL NEAR THE REAR DOORS, WHICH HAD NOT BEEN ACTIVATED. INSPECTION OF THE TOP TIER DRUMS SHOWED THE LADING TO BE LOADED WITH 9 ROWS OF 4 DRUMS EACH,AND 1 ROW (DOORWAY) OF 3 DRUMS EACH. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH COSCO, NEW JERSEY, WHICH COULD NOT PROVIDE ANY SHIPPER INFORMATION AS IT WAS AFTER NORMAL BUSINESS HOURS. IT WAS DECIDED THAT SINCE THE PRODUCT WAS NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING, THE CONTAINER WOULD REMAIN SECURED OVER NIGHT. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, COSCO, HOUSTON WAS CONTACTED AND THEY PROVIDED THEIR SHIPPER, ETS EXPRESS, WHICH TURNED OUT TO BE A BROKER. THE ETS CUSTOMER WAS IDENTIFIED AS EQUISTAR LYONDELL OUT OF CHANNEL VIEW, TEXAS. LYONDELL ADVISED THE DRUMS WERE LOADED BY SOUTH COAST TERMINALS, UNDER CONTRACT FOR LYONDELL. LYONDELL MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO REMOVE THE LADING, INSPECT, AND LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUMS <S>. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS IT WAS NOTED THE AFT TY-PATCH APPEARED TO HAVE PULLED AWAY FROM THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALL ON BOTH SIDES OF THE CONTAINER. FROM THE 2ND AND 3RD ROW OF DRUMS FROM THE REAR, THE TY-PATCH WAS 'HIGH SPOTTED' AND NOT FULLY ATTACHED TO THE RECESSED PORTIONS OF THE WALLS. IF THE TY-PATCH HAD BEEN APPLIED WITH FULL CONTACT, IT HAD PULLED LOOSE FROM THE RECESSED AREAS, WHICH WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THE MOVEMENT OF THE DRUMS ON BOTH TIERS. MID WAY INTO THE LOAD, THE CENTER FORWARD AREA OF DRUM WERE ALSO TY-PATCHED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT. THIS WOULD BE THE PROPER APPLICATION TO SECURE 1/2 OF THE LADING, HOWEVER, THE LAST (5TH ROW OF DRUMS FROM THE NOSE) ROW CONSISTED OF A ROW OF 4, RATHER THAN A ROW OF 3 DRUMS. THIS IS NOT RECOMMENDED METHOD PER THE TY-PATCH INSTALLATION PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE COLTON YARD. DEVELOPED THE CAR WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR BY A CREW WORKING ON AN ADJACENT TRACK. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD, LOCATED THE TANK CAR IN BOWL TRACK #25, AND OBSERVED THE MANWAY COVER PLATE TO BE IN THE FULLY OPEN POSITION. IT APPEARS THE COVER PLATE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED, AND WHEN THE CAR WENT OVER THE HUMP AND IMPACTED  THE  OTHERS CARS IN THE TRACK, THE LIQUID SURGE FORCED THE COVER PLATE OPEN. THE COVER PLATE HAD FLIPPED BACK BEYOND THE STOP PIN AND WAS RESTING ON THE TOP SHELL OF THE CAR. INSPECTION OF THE 8 SWING BOLTS SHOWED THEM TO BE IN PERFECT WORKING CONDITION, AND IT IS PRESUMED THEY WERE NOT IN PLACE TO SECURE THE COVER PLATE, OTHERWISE THEY WOULD AVE SHOWED SOME FORM OF DAMAGE WHEN THE COVER PLATE FLIPPED BACK. A BUMPER JACK HAD TO BE USED TO FORCE THE COVER PLATE BACK PAST THE STOP PIN. AS THE GASKET APPEARED TO B IN GOD CONDITION, THE COVER PLATE WAS CLOSED AND PROPERLY SECURED. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE DISCREPANCY FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED FOR NOTIFICATION PURPOSES. THE FOLLOWING DAY, THE SHIPPER ADVISED THE CAR HAD BEEN AT THE CONSIGNEES FACILITY THE PREVIOUS WEEK, WHERE THEY OPENED THE CAR TO PULL A PRODUCT SAMPLE. IT APPEARS THEY DID NOT PROPERLY SECURE THE CAR AFTER OBTAINING THE SAMPLE, AND THE CAR WAS PULLED FROM THE FACILITY, EVENTUALLY WINDING UP IN COLTON. THE CAR HAS BEEN RESCHEDULED TO MOVE BACK TO THE CONSIGNEE.

SIMPLOT, WHO WILL HAVE THE PACKING REPLACED ONCE THE CAR IS RECEIVED AT POCATELLO, IDAHO. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT PHOENIX, AZ. MANAGER COOPER WAS CONFERENCED WITH PHOENIX YARDMASTER JACK DEMPSEY, WHO STATED THE CAR DEPARTMENT NOTED THE CAR DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT A RATE OF 10-15 DROPS PER MINUTE. ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE(ERI), THE RAILROADS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND AND ATTEMPT TO REPAIR THE CAR. THE CAR WAS LOCATED ON YARD TRACK#3, WHICH ALLOWED ROAD ACCESS TO THE CAR WITHOUT HAVING TO MOVE IT. ERI INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT PRODUCT WAS BY PASSING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND ALSO BY PASSING THE BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE CAP. ATTEMPTS TO WORK THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE IN ORDER TO GET IT TO SEAT PROPERLY FAILED. THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS REMOVED, AND GORE-TEX GASKET MATERIAL PLACED IN THE  BOTTOM OF THE CAP. TEFLON TAPE WAS USED TO COAT THE THREADS OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE, THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP REINSTALLED,  AND TIGHTENED TO SECURE THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. ATTEMPTS TO LOCATE THE SHIPPER, MUREX INITIALLY FAILED AS THE WAYBILL INFORMATION SHOWED THE BNSF AS THE SHIPPER OF RECORD. THE CONSIGNEE, CHEVRON, WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO OFF LOAD THE CAR AS SOON AS POSSIBLE ACCOUNT THE CONDITION OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. CHEVRON, RICHMOND, CALIFORNIA PROVIDED A CONTACT NUMBER FOR MUREX. HOWEVER, IT TURNED OUT TO BE AN OFFICE NUMBER AND THERE WAS NO RESPONSE DUE TO THE HOLIDAY WEEKEND. ON MONDAY MORNING, THE BNSF SERVICE DESK WAS CONTACTED, AND THEY PROVIDED A BILL OF LADING THAT SHOWED THE SHIPPER AS MUREX, CARE OF STANTRANS INC., TEXAS CITY, TEXAS. DEVELOPED MUREX PROVIDES THE PRODUCT TO CHEVRON, AND STANTRANS LOADS THE RAILCARS UNDER CONTRACT TO MUREX. MUREX WAS NOTIFIED TO HAVE THE CAR SHOPPED AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE INSPECTED UPON IT'S RETURN TO TEXAS CITY. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES.
