column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT BOWIE, AZ DEVELOPED A BRYAN PAULMER WITH THE ARIZONA EASTERN RAILROAD HAD INSPECTED SEVERAL TANK CARS INTERCHANGED TO THEM FROM THE UP ON 11-19, AND FOUND THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. MR. PAULMER CONTACTED UP CAR DEPARTMENT, TUSCON, AZ., WHO THEN NOTIFIED RMCC OF THE INCIDENT. THIS IS THE SAME CAR THAT CTS MANAGER JOHNSON HAD A RESPONSE TO ON 11-22. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE (ERI), THE RAILROAD'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CONTRACTOR, AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND AND ATTEMPT TO REPAIR THE CAR. ERI INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE PRODUCT  WAS BY PASSING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND ALSO BY PASSING THE BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE CAP, AT A RATE OF 2-3 DROPS PER MINUTE. ATTEMPTS TO OPERATE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO GET IT TO SEAT FAILED. AFTER CAREFUL EXAMINATION OF THE VALVE, THE OUTLET CAP WAS REMOVED, AND TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE. GORE-TEX GASKET MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTLET CAP, THE CAP REINSTALLED AND TIGHTENED, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. ATTEMPTS TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER FAILED AS THEY ARE NOT REGISTERED WITH CHEMTREC, EVEN THOUGH THE WAY BILL HAD CHEMTREC AS THE EMERGENCY CONTACT. A CONTACT WAS MADE WITH PENRECO, PENNSYLVANIA, WHO PROVIDED A LOCAL NUMBER FOR PENRECO, HOUSTON. DEVELOPED PENRECO BUYS THE PRODUCT FROM CONOCO, WHO LOADS AND SHIPS THE CARS UNDER CONTRACT TO PENRECO. CONOCO IS THE CAR OWNER OF RECORD, AND THEY WERE ADVISED TO HAVE THE CAR SHOPPED TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE UPON IT'S RETURN TO WEST LAKE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY APL-PACER FORCES REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE EAST YARD. DEVELOPED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS BEING PICKED UP BY A DRAYMAN TO DELIVER WHEN HE NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE UNDER FRAME NEAR THE CHASSIS LANDING GEAR.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD. LOCATED THE CONTAINER IN RED #056, AND OBSERVED A SMALL POOL (LESS THAN 1 PINT) ON THE PAVEMENT UNDER THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA WHERE IT COULD BE GROUNDED AND SECURED PENDING INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE DOORS, NOTED THE LADING CONSISTED OF 5 GALLON POLY PAILS, STACKED 36 PER PALLET. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO SECURE THE LADING. THE PAILS HAD BEEN LIGHTLY STRETCH WRAPPED, AND WITH NO FORM OF BLOCKING IN PLACE, THE PALLETS MOVED DURING TRANSIT, ALLOWING THE PAILS TO TOPPLE, THE CONTENTS WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED TO LOCATE THE LEAKING PAIL(S). THREE PAILS WERE LOCATED THAT WERE DAMAGE WHEN THE LADING TOPPLED. ONE PAIL HAD THE BOTTOM PORTION CRACKED FROM TOPPLED FREIGHT AND LOST THE ENTIRE CONTENTS. ONE ADDITIONAL PAIL WAS LOCATED WITH A DAMAGED LID FROM THE PAILS FALLING INTO IT, WHICH LOST APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  ONE ADDITIONAL PAIL OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE WAS LOCATED THAT HAD A CRACKED LID ACCOUNT PAILS TOPPLING ONTO IT, WHICH LOST APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT. THE DAMAGED LIDS WERE REPLACED AND THE REMAINING PAILS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE. THE LADING WAS TRANSFERRED INTO CONTAINER GSTU 800133, PROPERLY SECURED, BLOCKED AND BRACED, THE RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED. IT WAS THEN RELEASED TO APL. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY APL-PACER FORCES REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE EAST YARD. DEVELOPED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS BEING PICKED UP BY A DRAYMAN TO DELIVER WHEN HE NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE UNDER FRAME. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO  THE EAST YARD, LOCATED THE CONTAINER IN BLACK #30 AND OBSERVED A SMALL POOL (LESS THAN 1 PINT) OF PRODUCT ON THE PAVEMENT UNDER THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA WHERE IT COULD BE GROUNDED AND SECURED PENDING INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE DOORS, NOTED THE LADING TO BE 5 GALLON POLY PAILS, STACKED 36 TO PALLET. A TOTAL OF 20 PALLETS FILLED THE CONTAINER. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO SECURE THE LADING. THE PAILS HAD BEEN LIGHTLY STRETCH WRAPPED, AND WITH NO BLOCKING IN PLACE, THE PALLETS MOVED DURING TRANSIT, ALLOWING THE PAILS TO TOPPLE. EIGHTEEN OF THE 20 PALLETS HAD TOPPLED TOWARDS THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER. THE CONTENTS WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED TO LOCATE THE LEAKING PAIL(S). A TOTAL OF 10 PAILS OF THE HAZARDOUS COMMODITY WERE FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED. TWO PAILS WERE CRUSHED FROM THE FALLING FREIGHT, LOSING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS. EIGHT OTHERS HAD THE LIDS DAMAGED AND CRACKED, ALL LOSING LESS THAN ONE GALLON A PIECE. SIXTEEN ADDITIONAL PAILS OF AN UNREGULATED PRODUCT WERE FOUND TO ALSO BE LEAKING. THE LOAD WAS REORGANIZED, AND WHERE REPLACEMENT LIDS COULD BE USED, THE PAILS WERE SECURED. THE REMAINING DAMAGED PAILS OF PRODUCT WERE DUMPED INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM FOR REPACKAGING AT THE WAREHOUSE. THE CONTAINER WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED, THEN RELOADED WITH THE ORIGINAL FREIGHT. THE LADING WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED, THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF, LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN YELLOW #49  AND NOTED A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN ONE PINT) ON THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE CONTAINER. AS THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE, IT WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND SECURED PENDING INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, NOTED THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON DRUMS. FLOOR LOADED, AND VOID OF ANY BLOCKING OR BRACING. THE DRUMS HAD SHIFTED TOWARDS THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER AND WERE STILL UPRIGHT. THE WAY BILL AND A BILL OF LADING LOCATED WITHIN THE CONTAINER, LISTED THE HAZARDOUS CONTENTS  AS 8 DRUMS OF CORROSIVES.  8 POLY DRUMS WERE FOUND IN THE CENTER OF THE LOAD WHICH WERE IDENTIFIED AS THE LISTED HAZARDOUS COMMODITY. THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THESE DRUMS. INSPECTION OF THE NOSE AREA PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM<S> WITHIN THE FIRST 2 ROWS OF DRUMS. ONCE THE SHIPPER WAS LOCATED, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE LADING, INSPECT THE DRUMS, AND LOCATED THE SUSPECTED LEAKER<S> UPON REACHING AND REMOVING THE FIRST ROW OF DRUMS FROM THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, LOCATED ONE DRUM 2ND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDE WALL, THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP. THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP HAD A PERFECT 90 DEGREE 'L' SHAPED DENT. WHICH INDICATED THIS DRUM HAD BEEN DAMAGED PRIOR TO LOADING, AS THERE WAS NO LIKE TYPE DAMAGE TO ANY OF THE ADJACENT DRUMS. THE DENT DEVELOPED A SMALL CRACK WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO WEEP DURING TRANSIT. DEVELOPED THIS DRUM, AND THE ADJACENT DRUM,  WERE LABELED AS A CORROSIVE. THE PRODUCT WAS IDENTIFIED AS AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. (N-BUTYLETHANOLAMINE). AND NEITHER WERE DECLARED ON THE BILL OF LADING OR THE RAIL WAYBILL. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED INTO AN OVERPACK FOR SECUREMENT. THE RESIDUE WAS NEUTRALIZED, THE FLOOR CLEANED, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM. THE LADING WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR OVER THE ROAD LOCAL DELIVER, AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATION WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  DEVELOPED A DRAYMAN WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK UP THE CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY, AND WHILE BEING CHECKED OUT, NOTED A LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE FRONT UNDERFRAME.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF, OPENED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND THE LADING TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED.  THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS NOT TO AAR BOE 6C STANDARD, HOWEVER, APPEARED TO BE SUFFICIENT TO RESTRAIN THE LADING.  ONE OF THE CROSS MEMBER BULL BOARDS WAS LAYING ON THE DECK OF THE CONTAINER AND IT IS NOT SURE IF THE BOARD HAD EVER BEEN ATTACHED TO THE MAIN BULKHEAD, AS THERE WERE NO NAILS OBSERVED IN THE BOARD.  MOL WAS CONTACTED, AND THEY PROVIDED THEIR SHIPPER, LUBRIZOL.  LUBRIZOL MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE LADING REMOVED AND INSPECTED TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM(S).  ONE DRUM WAS LOCATED IN THE BOTTOM NOSE ROW, 2ND FROM THE LEFT SIDE WALL, THAT WAS IDENTIFIED AS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE DRUM HAD CAVED IN AT THE LOWER ROLLING HOOP.  THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE IS TYPICAL WHEN THE DRUM HAS BEEN DROPPED, AS THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS OF LIKE TYPE DAMAGE ON THE ADJACENT DRUMS.  IT APPEARS THE DRUM HAD BEEN DAMAGED PRIOR TO OR DURING THE LOADING PROCESS.  WITH THE INWARD DEFLECTION OF THE ROLLING HOOP, THE METAL STRESSED AND FORMED A ONE INCH CRACK.  THE LIQUID HYDRAULICS WITHIN THE DRUM DURING TRANSIT CAUSED THE CRACK TO EXPAND, RELEASING THE PRODUCT.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK FOR RETURN TO THE MANFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. ONCE THE LADING WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: NOVEMBER 29TH, 2000, 07:45- A CALL WAS RECEIVED BY RON NORMAN FROM LT. JOHNSON OF THE AYER, MASSACHUSETTS FIRE DEPT., INFORMING METHANEX CORPORATION OF A LEAKING RAILCAR. THE CAR IS LEAKING 500 DROPS/MIN.  THEY WERE ADVISED TO CONTAIN THE LEAK IN A PAIL.  CAR #ACFX-71179.  08:15- LT. JOHNSON OF THE AYER FIRE DEPT. WAS CONTACTED (978-772-8231).  HE CONFIRMED THAT THE BOTTOM FLANGE WAS LEAKING.  HE STATED THAT THE HAZMAT CONTROL TEAM WAS ON SCENE WITH THE FIRE DEPT. TEMPERATURE IS 45 F AND SUNNY.  HE ALSO STATED THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED.  WE REQUESTED TO TALK WITH THE ON-SCENE COMMANDER AND HE STATED THAT HE WOULD HAVE HIM CALL US.  08:20- CONTACTED THE SITE LOADING CO-ORDINATOR TO SOURCE AN EMPTY RAILCAR TO OFFLOAD THE PRODUCT INTO.  SHE INFORMED US THAT THE LEAKING CAR WAS LOADED IN BAYONNE, NJ.  08:25- THE ON-SCENE COMMANDER, BOB PEDRAZZI OF AYER FIRE DEPT., CONTACTED US.  HE STATED THAT THEY WERE CONTAINING THE LEAK IN SAND AS PER THE GUIDEBOOK.  WE SUGGESTED HE COULD CONTAIN IN A BUCKET AND MOVE PRODUCT TO A BARREL OR POUR BACK IN THE CAR.  HE STATED HE WAS FOLLOWING THE HAZMAT BOOK AND WAS GOING TO CONTINUE TO CONTAIN IN SAND.  WE ASKED WHAT ASSISTANCE WE COULD PROVIDE.  HE KNEW THE PRODUCT WAS GOING TO FOX PACKAGING AND GAVE US A PHONE NUMBER (508-840-2837).  HE THOUGHT THAT THEY MIGHT BE ABLE TO HELP OR PROVIDE AND EMPTY RAILCAR.  WE INFORMED BOB PEDRAZZI THAT WE WOULD ARRANGE SOMEONE TO COMPLETE THE TRANSFER AND FIND AN EMPTY RAILCAR OR TRUCKS.  WE OFFERED TO FAX AN MSDS TO THEM.  FAX NUMBER IS 978-772-8230.  (FAX SENT IMMEDIATELY).  HE GAVE US A PHONE NUMBER TO REACH HIM AT THE SCENE #508-840-2837.  THIS NUMBER DID NOT WORK.  08:40- PHONED FOX PACKAGING TO CONTACT DENNIS COLLACHY.  HE WAS NOT ON SITE AND THE ASSISTANT SAID THAT SHE WOULD GET SOMEONE TO CALL US.  08:43- TALKED WITH MARK AGUILAR, DALLAS, TO ARRANGE GETTING AN EMPTY RAILCAR TO THE SCENE. 08:45- PETER MASSMANIAN, MANAGER OF FOX PACKAGING CONTACTED US.  HE HAD BEEN AT THE INCIDENT AND GAVE US AN UPDATE.  HE HAD STATE THAT THE LEAK WAS 1- 2GALS/HR.  HE HAD OFFERED CONTAINERS, BUCKETS AND BARRELS, TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING PRODUCT.  THE FIRE DEPT. HAD STATED THAT THEY WOULD CONTINUE TO COLLECT IN SAND AS PER THE BOOK.  PETER GAVE US THE NUMBER OF CLEAN HARBOURS (781-849-1800), AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY WITHIN A COUPLE OF HOURS TRAVEL TIME.  HE ALSO GAVE US THE NAME OF JOHN LAW, EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR OF SAFETY FOR GILFORD RAILROAD (978-663-1023).  08:50- CONTACTED MARLIN TRAVEL TO RESEARCH FLIGHT OPTIONS TO THE SCENE.  EARLIEST POSSIBLE COMMERCIAL ARRIVAL WOULD BE 23:00 HRS.  08:52- CONTACTED THE TECH ADVISOR TO PLACE HIM ON STANDBY.  08:53- CONTACTED BY GEORGE CLEM WITH THE RAILROAD, FREIGHT AGENT FOR GILFORD RAIL (978-663-1023).  HE STATED THAT THEY WERE IN THE PROCESS OF GETTING AN EMPTY RAILCAR FROM FOX PACKAGING. EXPECTED THE EMPTY TO BE AT THE SCENE IN 1 1/2 - 2 WERE IN THE PROCESS OF GETTING AN EMPTY RAILCAR FROM FOX PACKAGING.  EXPECTED THE EMPTY TO BE AT THE SCENE IN 1 1/2

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON NOVEMBER 14, 2000 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 AM, WE RECEIVED A CALL THAT A FARMER ROLLED TWO NH3 TANKS IN A DITCH AT TWO DIFFERENT LOCATIONS.  ONE WAS ROLLED ON CLINTON AVENUE AND THE OTHER WAS ROLLED AT 330TH STREET.  BOTH TANKS WERE LEAKING NH3, DUE TO DAMAGE TO THE FRONT VALVES AND BEING UPSIDE DOWN IN THE DITCH.  A 911 CALL WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED TO DISPATCH THE REGION 5 HAZ MAT TEAM OUT OF FORT DODGE.  LOHRVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT TOOK CONTROL OF THE SCENE AND ESTABLISHED INCIDENT COMMAND.  A WRECKER WAS CALLED AND WHEN THE HAZ MAT TEAM ARRIVED WE WERE ABLE TO SET THE TANKS UPRIGHT WITH THE WRECKER.  THE TANKS WERE SET BACK ON THEIR WHEELS AND PULLED OUT INTO THE FIELD TO FINISH DISPENSING THE NH3 TO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE NH3 THAT WAS LOST WAS VENTED TO THE ATMOSPHERE AND WE DID NOT NEED TO CONTROL IT WITH WATER.  A TOTAL OF 8,420 POUNDS OF NH3 WAS RELEASED FROM BOTH TANKS; OF WHICH, 82% (6,904 POUNDS) WAS NITROGEN.  THE WIND WAS FROM THE NW AT MPH AND THE TEMPERATURE WAS 25.  NO ONE HAD TO BE EVACUATED AND NO FARM BUILDINGS HAD LIVESTOCK.  THE INCIDENT ENDED AT APPROXIMATELY 2 PM WITH AN EVALUATION THAT WE COULD NOT DO ANY FURTHER CLEAN UP AT THAT TIME. WE WILL EVALUATE THE SITES NEXT SPRING AND SEE IF WE NEED TO PROCEED FURTHER WITH ADDITIONAL CLEAN UP.  OUR BEST IDEA IS TO LET THE NH3 SPILL EVAPORATE INTO THE AIR SINCE IT WAS NOT CLOSE TO ANY WATERWAYS.  WE ARE STILL RECEIVING VERY LIMITED MOISTURE IN THAT AREA.  PLEASE FEEL FREE TO CALL ME AT 515-955-2040 WITH ANY ADDITIONAL QUESTIONS.

column168: THE SPILL OCCURRED DURING A FUEL OIL DELIVERY TO THE LEGANCZUK RESIDENCE ON NOVEMBER 11, 2000.  ACCORDING TO HL FUEL COMPANY, INC. PERSONNEL, A FUEL TRUCK DELIVERY LINE VALVE WAS INADVERTENTLY LEFT OPEN. APPROXIMATELY 30 TO 40 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL SPILLED ON THE TOP OF THE LEGANCZUK DRIVEWAY WHEN THE TRUCK'S POWER TAKE-OFF (PTO) WAS ENGAGED, CAUSING A TRANSFER PUMP TO ACTIVATE, SPILLING THE FUEL.  HL FUELS PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTACT THE NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION (NYSDEC) SPILL HOTLINE AND VEC TO BEGIN A CLEAN UP.
